{
  "__template_notes": [
    "Same template as staging.spec.json.template. Diffs ONLY in name/workersMin/workersMax/env.<APP>_ENVIRONMENT.",
    "If you find yourself adding another delta (e.g., agent-runtime flag, a capacity setting), resist. Production should run the same image and same config as staging; that's how the drift audit catches drift.",
    "DO NOT add your <APP>_OFFLINE_FIXTURES and <APP>_DETERMINISTIC_OVERRIDES equivalents to env — anti-cheating contract requires them UNSET.",
    "PORT_HEALTH is MANDATORY (env block, same value as PORT for the standard single-port case). RunPod's LB poller uses PORT_HEALTH (NOT PORT) to find /ping. If PORT_HEALTH is missing, the worker boots cleanly, FastAPI serves /ping 204/200, but the gateway never sees it and the endpoint stays `unhealthy` forever with NO ERROR in any log. This is the silent killer — see pitfalls-35.md #25 and setup-guide §6.1.2. The deploy script must refuse any LB spec without PORT_HEALTH.",
    "dockerStartCmd is MANDATORY on every spec — never omit. RunPod IGNORES the Dockerfile's CMD when the base image already declares its own (TEI, TGI, vLLM, NIM, Whisper, faster-whisper, etc. all ship one). Without dockerStartCmd, the base image's binary runs in place of your start.sh, dies with no args in milliseconds, and the worker exits code 1 with an EMPTY Container logs panel — looks identical to a corrupt image. See pitfalls-35.md #26 and setup-guide §6.1.3. The deploy script must refuse any spec without it.",
    "Companion to dockerStartCmd: the Dockerfile MUST set an explicit ENTRYPOINT (NOT `ENTRYPOINT []`). Use `ENTRYPOINT [\"bash\", \"/app/start.sh\"]` and `CMD []`. The empty-array form is supposed to clear the inherited entrypoint per the OCI spec, but RunPod's runtime doesn't honor it reliably — the base image's inherited entrypoint hijacks dockerStartCmd as args, model-server dies in milliseconds, worker exits code 1 with empty Container logs EVEN THOUGH dockerStartCmd is set correctly. See pitfalls-35.md #27 and setup-guide section 6.1.4.",
    "DO NOT hard-code HF_HOME or HUGGINGFACE_HUB_CACHE in env. Let start.sh / boot.py do runtime detection: read from /runpod-volume/huggingface-cache/hub (RunPod's host-cached models, populated by spec.modelName) when present, fall back to /tmp. Hard-coding /tmp here defeats FlashBoot — every scale-from-zero re-downloads the entire model (3-5 min for 7-8 GB, often gateway-times-out). /runpod-volume here is NOT a user-attached Network Volume — it's a host-local cache mount, does NOT pin region (different mechanism from pitfall #23). See pitfalls-35.md #30 and setup-guide section 6.1.7.",
    "DO NOT use workersMin: 1 + flashBootType: OFF as a workaround for /ping timeouts. That combination defeats the entire serverless cost model (~$35-95/day for 5 endpoints always-warm). The actual cause of /ping timeouts is one of pitfalls #25-#31. Walk the silent-killers checklist; do not mask root causes with always-warm.",
    "DO NOT rely on bash `:=` or Python `setdefault` to set HF cache vars in start.sh / boot.py. TEI/TGI/vLLM/NIM/Whisper bases preset HUGGINGFACE_HUB_CACHE=/data (and similar) in image ENV; conditional assignment becomes a NO-OP and your runtime detection is silently ignored. The hf_cache_resolved log says `runpod-host` but `printenv` inside the container shows `/data`, model loader hangs forever on ENOENT with no error. Use UNCONDITIONAL assignment: `HUGGINGFACE_HUB_CACHE=\"...\"` in bash, `os.environ[\"HUGGINGFACE_HUB_CACHE\"] = \"...\"` in Python. See pitfalls-35.md #31 and setup-guide section 6.1.8.",
    "Spec env-var keys MUST match what the application actually reads. If app.py has `os.getenv(\"QWEN3_RERANKER_MODEL_PATH\", \"/runpod-volume/models/Qwen3-Reranker-8B\")`, setting `\"MODEL_PATH\": \"...\"` in spec env is a SILENT NO-OP — the app falls through to its stale pod-based default and worker dies with `RuntimeError: model path does not exist`. Run the parity audit `comm -23 <(spec env keys) <(grep os.getenv app.py keys)` on every (spec, app) pair. See pitfalls-35.md #32 and setup-guide section 6.1.9.",
    "Background-load pattern in app.py: the `_target` thread MUST set `self._load_error = f\"{type(exc).__name__}: {exc}\"` in its `except Exception:` block. Without it, load failure is silent — `load_state()` falls back to \"idle\", next /ping spawns a fresh thread that crashes identically, /ping returns 204 (initializing) forever, and the gateway hangs external requests until executionTimeoutMs. The traceback IS in container logs but never affects /ping's contract. See pitfalls-35.md #33 and setup-guide section 6.1.10.",
    "Worker Dockerfile MUST set `ENV HF_HUB_ENABLE_HF_TRANSFER=0` (or requirements.txt MUST include `hf_transfer>=0.1.6`). The runpod/pytorch / vllm/vllm-openai / TEI base images preset `HF_HUB_ENABLE_HF_TRANSFER=1` in their image ENV, but `hf_transfer` is an optional package. Without one of the two fixes, every snapshot_download / hf_hub_download call raises `ValueError: Fast download using 'hf_transfer' is enabled but 'hf_transfer' package is not available`. See pitfalls-35.md #34 and setup-guide section 6.1.11.",
    "RIGHT-SIZE `containerDiskInGb` and `gpuIds` AGGRESSIVELY. Over-provisioning shrinks the scheduler's eligible host pool. Formula: `containerDiskInGb = model_size_gb + 5 + (5 if vLLM else 0)`, rounded UP to nearest 5. Disk does NOT need to fit the Docker image (read-only overlay) or the model when FlashBoot hits (lives at `/runpod-volume/...`, not counted). Same for `gpuIds`: a 4B model fits in 24GB VRAM — use `ADA_24,AMPERE_24,ADA_48_PRO,AMPERE_48` (NOT just 48GB+). The 24GB pool is 5-10× larger than 48GB. Setting 80GB disk when 30GB is enough excludes ~70% of the global fleet. See pitfalls-35.md #35 and setup-guide section 6.1.12."
  ],
  "name": "<APP>-production",
  "endpointType": "LOAD_BALANCER",
  "registryImage": "${DEPLOY_REGISTRY_IMAGE}",
  "publicRegistry": false,
  "registryAuthName": "ghcr-<APP>",
  "registryUsername": "<GHCR_OWNER>",
  "registryPasswordEnv": "GHCR_PAT",
  "templateName": "<APP>-production-template",
  "containerDiskInGb": 30,
  "ports": [
    "8080/http"
  ],
  "dockerStartCmd": [
    "bash",
    "/app/services/<APP>/start.sh"
  ],
  "gpuIds": "BLACKWELL_96,BLACKWELL_180,HOPPER_141",
  "gpuTypeIds": [
    "NVIDIA B200",
    "NVIDIA RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell Server Edition",
    "NVIDIA RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell Workstation Edition",
    "NVIDIA H200",
    "NVIDIA H200 NVL",
    "NVIDIA H100 NVL"
  ],
  "modelName": "<HF_REPO>",
  "gpuCount": 1,
  "_locations_note": "DO NOT add dataCenterIds / locations / region / etc. Endpoints MUST be GLOBAL — see pitfalls-35.md #23. The deploy script's _reject_region_pinning() will refuse any spec that pins a region.",
  "workersMin": 1,
  "workersMax": 2,
  "idleTimeout": 300,
  "executionTimeoutMs": 330000,
  "scalerType": "REQUEST_COUNT",
  "scalerValue": 1,
  "flashboot": true,
  "allowedCudaVersions": [
    "13.0",
    "12.8"
  ],
  "env": {
    "<APP>_HF_MODEL_REPO": "<HF_REPO>",
    "<APP>_HF_MODEL_REVISION": "<HF_REVISION>",
    "HF_TOKEN": "${HF_TOKEN}",
    "<APP>_WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/tmp/<APP>-workspaces",
    "<APP>_DISABLE_MODEL_FALLBACK": "0",
    "<APP>_USE_AGENT_RUNTIME": "1",
    "<APP>_MODE": "BENCHMARK_SAFE",
    "<APP>_ENVIRONMENT": "production",
    "PORT": "8080",
    "PORT_HEALTH": "8080",
    "<APP_REQUIRED_KEY>": "${<APP_REQUIRED_KEY>}"
  }
}
